PART III: THE CONVERGENCE THEOREM

III.1 Statement

For any irrational constant K and any exponent m, as the number of digits N increases:

```
lim_{N→∞} L_m(K, N) = C_K
```

where L_m(K, N) uses the first N digits of K_frac in the reversal.

III.2 Proof

Let R(K, N) = reverse( first N digits of K_frac ) + n/10.

Then R(K, N) ≥ 10^(N-1).

Therefore:

```
|T_m(K, N)| = 1000 × (K_frac)⁻ᵐ / R(K, N) ≤ 1000 × (K_frac)⁻ᵐ × 10^(1-N) → 0 as N→∞
```

Thus L_m(K, N) = T_m(K, N) + C_K → C_K. ∎

III.3 Rate of Convergence

The error decreases exponentially: |L_m(K, N) - C_K| ≈ 10^(1-N) × 1000 × (K_frac)⁻ᵐ.

Each additional digit multiplies accuracy by 10.

